# Idea and Concept

I had the idea for this project close to midnight when reminiscing about a game that I used to play on my dad's smartphone when I was much younger. It was very similar to Doodle Jump, but instead of being some cute alien thing with a snout, you were a green long-legged frog.  
One other big difference was that when you reached certain heights in that game, the background would change to something fitting. At the start it would just be the earth, then you'd only see the sky and clouds, and at some point, you'd even reach space. I think the game ended then, because as far as I know, no frog should be able to survive in space, but I don't fully recall that part of the game anymore.

While I was reminiscing about that game, I wondered how I could potentially put my own spin on these kinds of games and then I had a moment of clarity, sent straight from the heavens: "What if the frog was in hell?!".

From that point on the idea evolved into "What if Lucifer had to jump all the way up to heaven to talk with god?". Based on that idea I started with this little game development adventure.

# Project Setup

After figuring out the concept, I worked on setting up everything for the project and made some decisions to better define how the whole thing should work.

I decided to create the game with Unity, as I already have some experience with the engine and know that it has very good support for making 2D games. I also wanted to come up with many of the mechanics and features myself, to expand upon my base knowledge of game design and programming, which is why I decided against using game engines like "RPG Maker" where much is already prebuilt.

I also chose to create most if not all of the sprites and assets myself, to acquire some new skills and get better at making my own art. That is also why I decided to design everything as pixel art, because that is the style I'm most experienced with. As the characters for the game are also not very common in games (characters from Christianity), I had my doubts that there would be asset packs or the like which I could use for them, so I chose to do all the assets by myself, which also will have the benefit of keeping the design coherent throughout the whole game.

Aseprite would be the software in which I design the sprites, as it is specialised for pixel art and is the most used software in the industry for pixel art games (at least to my knowledge). I had also chosen it in hopes that the workflow would be shorter and in turn faster using the simple and limited feature set from Aseprite compared to the more complex graphic design tools like Krita or Photoshop.

For the gameplay, I chose to create three stages for this initial version of the game, as it makes sense story wise and gives just enough variety to keep players interested in what will happen next. The three stages can easily be set in the three realms of Christianity: Hell, Earth and Heaven. But it could also be expanded upon at a later time by including multiple circles of hell as written about in Dantes "Divine Comedy" or by adding more stages after heaven, maybe things like the chamber of God, space, or Paradiso which would also come from the "Divine Comedy".

To keep the gameplay interesting on subsequent playthroughs/runs, I wanted to have the platforms in my game spawn more or less at random, just like in "Doodle Jump". This would make every playthrough unique and lead to different challenges each time.

It would also pave the way for different game modes in the future, maybe something like an infinite mode where new platforms are always generated and the goal is to just get as high as possible before falling.

After making these decisions, I created a kanban-board with Trello to keep track of my tasks thorough the development and sort them by type or by importance.

I've also created a work log in Excel to track my progress and how long I worked on the project each day and on what tasks. The information gathered from this Excel file was then used to create the work log in this documentation, which summarizes the progress in weeks and gives a few extra details about the main parts of the work that happened during those weeks.

## Week 2 - Platform Logic and Camera Movement

Worked Hours: 18.5h

Progress report TLDR:

- Fixed issues with moving platforms
- Upgraded Platform Generator algorithm (still has some flaws)
- Implemented camera movement, based on the last reached platform

Progress report:

I sadly couldn't work on the project as much as I would have liked to this week, as I had some obligatory events I needed to attend.

I managed to fix the problems with the moving platforms from week one, by changing how I keep the player locked on the platform. After trying too long last week to create code that adds the movement of the platform to the velocity of the player, I decided to switch over to a different approach by just parenting the player object to the platform object. This worked well enough and I decided to move on for now. I initially didn't want to do the parenting approach, as it can lead to problems when having interpolation enabled on the characters RigidBody, but as I don't yet have any need for interpolation, I'll just leave it disabled and instead get the benefits of working platforms and also less headaches.

Most of this week's project time went into the platform generation algorithm. I wanted to get this working right, as it is basically the main core of the whole game. In the end it became quite complicated, mainly due to all the additional calculations necessary for moving platforms.

For better readability, I will set a naming convention from this point on, as we will be comparing two platforms a lot. The platform that has already been generated and from which we calculate the next platform will be named "PreviousPlatform" and the name for the platform we'd like to generate from this PreviousPlatform will be "NewPlatform".

The platform generation algorithm currently works somewhat like this:

Every platform-type has two areas. An area where no other platforms should be placed (because the platform itself needs that area) and an area where the player can get to, from said platform. These two areas are currently called "BlockedArea" and "ReachableArea".

Example of the areas, with BlockedArea marked in red and ReachableArea in green

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Simply put, the NewPlatform needs to spawn somewhere inside the ReachableArea of the PreviousPlatform, but not inside the BlockedArea. This is the basis for the whole algorithm, but to better integrate it into the game, we need some additional checks.

We also need to look out for the BlockedArea of the NewPlatform. Else the NewPlatform might be a moving platform and move into the BlockedArea of the PreviousPlatform. So instead of comparing the NewPlatform itself with the BlockedArea of the PreviousPlatform, we compare both their BlockedAreas and make sure that there is no overlap. Additionally, we want to make sure that no platform is placed horizontally outside of our screen area, else the player won't be able to get to it. To fix this we also need to check that the full BlockedArea of the NewPlatform will be inside of our screen area.

Putting this all together, we get something like this:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The way I've implemented this algorithm, all of it can be tweaked quite easily. The areas are calculated depending on the platform's properties (moving, higher jump, etc.) and thus will automatically adjust if we want to have bigger or smaller platforms, or if we want to make a moving platform that also works as a jump boost.

They also factor in the players jump height and width, so if I decide to later increase the default jump height of the player, The ReachableAreas will also adjust accordingly.

There are also some drawbacks to how this works. For every new property a platform can have, I need to update the calculations. If I'd want to make a platform that gives the player a double jump, I will need to add in a new code block in the calculation for how this changes the ReachableArea. Also, the areas and the platforms are currently generated at the start of the game and are static after that. So if I would give upgrades to the player, for example a double jump or a rocket boost, I wouldn't be able to have the future platforms further apart, because they've all already been generated.

But I think that the pros outweigh the cons here as the algorithm allows me to mix and match platform properties, making the game more varied without having to add a lot of extra work, and for the player powerups, I can just bind them to platforms as properties, so if the player should have a double jump, I can create a double jump platform. Another way would be to bind the powerups to the stages. So if I'd want the player to have a double jump in the second stage, I can just add that in the calculations of the ReachableAreas, so that every ReachableArea in the second stage is adjusted for the further reach of the player.

Known issues:

- Platforms can still spawn inside of each other sometimes, mainly with vertically moving platforms. This is because their BlockedArea currently goes far below their centre point and can overlap with platforms far below them. In the following picture, the left blue platform overlaps with the lower white platform. This was possible here because the blue platform was generated with the other blue platform as the PreviousPlatform and as their BlockedAreas don't overlap, the position was deemed adequate. But there was never a comparison between the left blue platforms BlockedArea and the lower white platforms BlockedArea, which is why it was possible for their BlockedAreas to overlap. This might become more of an issue moving forward, but for now I could just adjust the vertical movement of platforms to only go upwards, so that they cannot overlap with platforms below them.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- One of the things that also needs to be addressed is the basic calculation of the ReachableArea. Currently it is defined as a Vector2 with the players jump height as y and the jump width as x. But that means that the upper corners are not reachable because the jump height is not always at its maximum during a sideways jump. I'm not sure how I will address this yet, as just reducing the ReachableArea will make all other jumps easier. Maybe some form of radial area would have been better, but since jump height and jump width aren't the same distance, you can't just make a circle with one radius and call it a day. As a short-term fix, I will make the whole area smaller and maybe at a later point I'll find a way to mathematically just round off the upper edges of the ReachableArea.

The second main task that I worked on during week 2 was the camera movement. This was thankfully easier than the platform generator, although it did need some thinking. The main question was: When should the camera move upwards?

I checked how it was done in "Doodle Jump". There, the camera will move upwards when the player moves up. This is most likely the easiest method, but not ideal for my version, as I want the player to be able to retry jumps. So maybe the player would miss a platform, but they manage to get back to the original platform or one further below. If the camera moved with the player during their attempted jump, the camera might have moved too far up, and the player can't get on to the lower platform anymore, giving them a game over. This would also be troublesome when the bosses are implemented at a later point in time. When the player has to evade attacks, not every jump would necessarily be meant to advance to the next platform, but just to evade, so having the camera move further up when just trying to evade might be bothersome or even make boss encounters not enjoyable at all.

I've therefore created my own camera movement, where the camera will move not to the player, but to the last platform that the player had reached. This should be a bit more forgiving and allow for more trial and error.

I've also added an offset variable to set the camera a bit further up, to give the player a better view of the route ahead.

Now that the camera could move, I could also implement the (first) game over possibility, which is falling below the camera. For now, I just added an "alive" variable on the player and set it to "false" when the players position is below the border of the camera.

## Week 3 - ProgressBar and Game Over

Worked hours: 16h

Progress report TLDR:

- Implemented extra logic for falling "game over"
- Implemented "ProgressBar" to visualize information about the game's length, maximum reached height and level changes
- Fixed "unreachable platforms" issue with Platform Generator algorithm

Progress report:

During the weekend I had the idea of showing the player falling all the way down to the start, when having a "game over". I thought this would be a nice idea since it will show how far the player has come and should not be difficult to implement.

For the implementation, all I did was add a bit more code to the camera, to follow the player downwards when he goes "game over" and add a new script to the PlatformGenerator object that disables the colliders on all platforms except the starting platform, so that the player doesn't just land on a platform somewhere half way down.

In the end, the whole implementation of this only took around 1 hour and brings a lot of value to the experience in my opinion, so this small side idea was likely worth it.

A main part of this weeks' time was spent on the height counter. When I had the initial idea for the counter, I intended for there to be two elements. A simple number that shows you the height as you progress upwards and a bar element that would show you your height in relation to the height of other spots, like the start of the next stages or the end of the game.

During the implementation I decided to fully skip the number element and just focus on the bar (named "ProgressBar" from here on out). Knowing the exact height that the player is on doesn't really help in any way and also would only work somewhat as a kind of score-system because once you reached the top, everyone would have the same score. This is why I chose to leave the exact number out and just give visual feedback on the progression with the ProgressBar.

The implementation of the ProgressBar itself wasn't a big issue. I just used multiple sliders stacked over each other to show different values of interest. One slider shows the exact height of the player, one shows the highest point the player has reached during the active run and other static sliders show the start/end points of the stages.

The issue was getting the values for these sliders, mainly the ones for the stages, as I haven't yet implemented stage logic into my PlatformGenerator script.

After updating my PlatformGenerator and adding a script to dynamically create sliders for each stage and automatically set the sliders heights, the rough version of the ProgressBar looks like this:

White: current height of the player

Green: Maximum height reached during the run

Red: start of the next stage

![](data:image/png;base64,)

During this week I also used some of my time to fix one of the issues I had with my current platform spawning logic. More specifically, the unreachable upper corners of my ReachableAreas. The problem there was, that the calculation for the reachable area uses the players jump height as its height and the jump width as its width, but as the player would jump on a path more like a parabola, there would be places in the calculated ReachableArea that would be impossible to reach.

The following picture is a visualisation of this problem where the green area is the ReachableArea, the red line is an approximation of the players jump path, and the yellow striped area shows where the player can't reach:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

My fix for this issue involves these two new circular areas. The blue one is a circle with the radius of the players jump width, while the yellow one is the same but for the jump height.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

As you can see in the picture, the combination of the ReachableArea (green) with the blue circle makes a distinction here between the real reachable area and the area the player cannot reach (the yellow striped area in the previous picture). That means by limiting the ReachableArea to be only inside of both green and blue, we get the real reachable area.

As you might have noticed, the yellow area wasn't mentioned yet. That's because in this example it is not needed. But for certain types of platforms, mainly those that augment the players jump height, the yellow area can be bigger than the blue area.

Example of a platform where the jump height circle is bigger than the jump width circle:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

We always want to use the bigger circle of the two to use in our calculations. If we would use the smaller one, we would miss places where the player could actually reach.

After including this in our calculations our platform spawning algorithm works somewhat like this:

- Get the camera borders (left and right side of the visible area).
- Get the ReachableArea and BlockedArea of both the PreviousPlatform and the NewPlatform.
- Choose a random point inside the PreviousPlatforms ReachableArea where the BlockedAreas don't overlap and the BlockedArea of the NewPlatform will be fully inside the camera borders.
- Get either the jump height circle or jump width circle (whichever is bigger) of the PreviousPlatform and check if the point chosen in step 3 is inside of that circle. If not, move the chosen point just inside of the circle, so that it becomes reachable.

Known issues:

This method solves one of our previous issues with the PlatformGenerator, but it also has some new ones.

- After we move the chosen point in step 4, we don't recheck if the BlockedAreas overlap. This shouldn't be an issue currently as no BlockedArea of any current platform is so big that it could overlap at that distance, but maybe with future platforms, this could become a problem.
- The distribution of platforms will be affected by this adjustment. When we move a point from outside the circle to be inside of the circle, we move it just enough to touch the circle, so basically to be on the border of it. This means that all the platforms that would normally spawn outside, now spawn on the border, making it more likely for a platform to be there than normally.  
  <br/>I might have to fix this at one point, but it's not a big problem and doesn't have any impact on the playability or enjoyment of the game, so I'd rather have an imperfect distribution than unreachable platforms.  
  <br/>I tried to visualise this change in distribution here. The points furthest out have some areas where they are very bunched up. Those are the areas where the points had been moved in, making those areas denser with platforms, showing that the chance of a platform spawning there will now be more likely than at other spots.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

During the update of the PlatformGenerator, I've also created a new component to handle general variables for the game. The so called "GameController". This component currently handles options for each stage like length and platform amount. Close to the end of development for this game, I wan't to be able to use the GameController to adjust difficulty and playtime of the game. This can be used to see, with which settings the game is most enjoyable, or to maybe create shorter and easier runs for small demos or maybe even make different game modes.

As a first step to have adjustable difficulty, I've also added a variable for each stage with which the SpawnableArea of all platforms on that stage can be augmented. With this, I can make platforms be closer together on easy levels and make them be further apart on more difficult levels.

I might add a second variable to add a zone around all platforms of a stage where no other platforms should spawn, basically the inverse of the previously mentioned variable. By increasing this, I can force platforms to always be further apart. This might be useful for harder difficulty stages where I want to drastically reduce the chance of easy jumps.

Nearly the full week was used to implement the main character. This was one part I was worried about the most, as the main character of a game is a major selling point and it can change the success of a game drastically. Because I don't have much experience with designing characters, I was dreading starting my work on this.

To get around this mental block, I first designed and implemented a very minor character for the game. He is currently just named "Servant", and he will be somewhat of a guide or tutorial for the story and the gameplay. I first wanted him to be an overly serious character, with a blocky form inspired by the main character of "Super Meat Boy" and with influence from "Philoctetes" from the Disney animated movie "Hercules", but I quickly realised that the initial design wasn't working well for the canvas size I chose. To address this, I pivoted to make the character more rounded, which also made him cuter. I wasn't sure if this new shape would still work with the more "serious" demeaner that I was aiming for, but I think in the end, the design worked out well. I added a small idle animation and imported him into Unity, to work with at a later time.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

After finishing the "Servant" character, I finally felt ready to start working on the main character of the game. I had some ideas for the design, mainly influenced by a certain form of the character "Eddie" from "Guilty Gear Strive". In that game, the jumping animation of "Eddie" was somewhat like a red and black devil, which I found very striking and wanted to use as reference for my character. I also thought that as a base, I could use the lobby characters of the same game, but that turned out to not work well with the chosen canvas size, so I instead searched for a pixel art template specifically for my canvas size.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

I went through a few iterations for the design and landed on something that I thought would fit well to my game.

Then came the difficult part.

**Animation**.

I already struggled on the idle animation, trying to figure out how to show subtle movement with only 28 pixels as height to work with. Then came the wings, which I needed a lot of references for in order to figure out how they should move. After I was done with that, last but not least: The running animation.

Thankfully there are a lot of resources, explaining how to do running animations on all sorts of scales and with all sorts of styles, so I closely followed a short tutorial by "slynyrd" on their blog, which I can definitely recommend to anyone with any interest in pixel art. Still, the running animation took a lot of time, and I also had to change the colours of some parts of my character to make the movement more readable during the animation.

In the end I had 8 animations with lengths ranging from 1 to 12 frames. Thankfully I was able to reuse some parts of those initial animations that I struggled with in later animations, which drastically shortened the time I needed for them.

When I was happy with the animations, I imported the Aseprite file into Unity and made a game object out of it. I thankfully had some experience with the Unity Animator, so going from the individual animations to a functional animator with correctly set up transitions didn't take much time.

## Week 6 - Sound Effects and Attacks

Worked hours: 42.25h

Progress report TLDR:

- Added sound effects to the players movement and to special platforms (high jump and breakable)
- Added ambience sounds for each stage type
- Added custom attack system

Progress report:

Now that two of the main parts were done (platforms and player), I wanted to start the implementation of something that would bridge and enhance the interactions between the two components. What I'm talking about is sound effects.

The main things that need sound effects would be the movement of the player, like walking, jumping and so on. But I also wanted some effects for the special platforms that execute logic when the player lands on them. These sound effects would (in theory) make it more obvious that the executed logic has happened, and that it was triggered by the player, and not by anything else. I was also thinking of adding different walking sounds to the player for different types of platforms, but as that might have needed a decent amount of custom logic, I chose to leave that feature out for this initial version.

All the sound effects for the platforms and the player are taken from "Pixabay", where people can upload their media and make it available for download with very open licensing, meaning that the media can be used and edited without issue, even in monetized products. Later I would find out that there are much better sites when it comes to sound effects specifically for games, but for this project I got most of the sounds from there.

When I found sounds that I like, I would download them, edit them with "Davinci Resolve" until I'm happy with the result, import them into Unity and play them over a custom Sound Manager Script, which was heavily inspired by the tutorial from "Small Hedge Games" and later expanded upon.

The editing in Davinci Resolve was mostly changing the length of the soundbites, giving small variations in pitch to create a less repetitive feeling for quickly repeating sounds (like walking or jumping) and changing the profile of some sounds to create a better soundscape when played in combination with other sounds.

View of the editing timeline in "Davinci Resolve". Having all the sfx on the same timeline helps with quickly comparing them to one another:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The custom sound manager would let me play global sounds from any script over the same Audio Source, which reduces complexity and makes it easy to add sounds fast to any gameobject. There are also custom "StateMachineBehaviour"-scripts which can be added in the animator to play sounds when transitioning between animations. These were quite helpful and kept the main scripts short, without extra logic to just play some sounds, but having the sounds split between normal Monobehaviour scripts and scripts in some animators can make it difficult to manage. Maybe for a bigger project, this would have to be handled some other way, but it worked well in this case.

After adding all the sound effects, I wanted to have some ambience tracks playing on each stage/level. This enhances the immersion by making the player hear how it would sound being in that environment and it would also be useful to have another thing signifying a transition when switching from one stage to the next, other than just the platform types.

For this I once again got some sounds from "Pixabay" that would fit the current 3 stages and edited them in "Davinci Resolve". But for these I needed to upgrade the sound manager, because these sounds should be able to loop (all the other sounds would just play once and then stop) and they should be able to transition from one stage ambience to the next to make the transition between stages feel a bit smoother and not like a direct switch.

To implement this extra functionality, I added two extra audio sources (ambience and ambienceSwitch) to the sound manager that were both set to loop and created a custom "PlayAmbience" function that would either play the given sound on the ambience audio source if no other sound was already playing or start a fade function. This fade function would fade out the sound on the ambience audio source while simultaneously fading in the new sound on the ambienceSwitch audio source, creating a simple crossfade. When the crossfade is done, the values of the ambienceSwitch source are copied over to the ambience source and the ambienceSwitch source is turned off again.

It only took me around half of the week for adding the audio, so I directly went further to the next main component, the bosses/enemies, which are meant to be the main difference between my game and the base inspiration "Doodle Jump".

Before adding bosses and attacks and sprites and all of that, I first had to come up with a system for how my bosses would be able to attack. I wanted something that makes it easy to create many variations of attacks fast, and where I could use the same system for all types of bosses. The attacks should also be able to have some randomness to them, so that the patterns aren't too easy to remember. What I didn't want to worry about yet was handling how much damage attacks do, and how or if the player could somehow fight back or defend himself other than dodging. For now, I just wanted the player to have to dodge every attack and just move further up instead of fighting back. All attacks would be "one-hit" and instantly end the run, so I'd have to keep that in mind when making the attack patterns, so that it's never impossible to dodge all attacks.

The system that I came up with uses the following parts:

- AttackData:  
  Contains information about how an attack will play out, where the attack instances should be spawned, how many should be spawned, how frequent the attack should be used, and so on. The Attack Prefab is also linked in the AttackData as the object that should be instantiated for the attack.
- Attack Prefab:  
  A GameObject with the sprites and colliders and any extra scripts or logic that is needed for the specific attack, for example if the attack is a projectile, the attack prefab will have a script for the movement/trajectory of the projectile.
- BossData:  
  Contains information about the boss, for example on which stage it should spawn or how long should be waited after the boss has spawned to start with the attacks. The bossData also contains a list of Attacks (more specifically AttackDatas) which defines what attacks the boss can use.
- Boss Prefab:  
  A GameObject with the sprites of the boss and any custom boss logic. The BossData is also contained on the Boss Prefab.
- AttackManager:  
  Contains a list of all spawnpoints for attacks. Executes attacks from the list of attacks on the given bosses BossData, until the boss despawns.
- GameController:  
  Manages many parts of the game loop. For the attack system, the GameController handles the spawning and despawning of the BossPrefabs.

To better understand how all these parts work together, let's go through how a boss encounter would work in the game.

The GameController always knows where the player currently is. For each stage, we have set specific heights on the GameController that the player must reach for the boss to spawn, or even further up for the boss to despawn again. When the player reaches the spawnheight for one of the stages, the GameController creates an instance of the Boss Prefab.

When instantiated, a script on the "Boss Prefab" will start a Coroutine on the AttackManager which will do the attacks of the boss until the boss despawns again.

The before mentioned Coroutine basically handles all the attacking, so let's go through how it does one attack:  
At the start, the coroutine chooses a random weighted AttackData from the list of AttackDatas on the bosses BossData. The chosen AttackData will be used to define, how the new attack should work. Based on the AttackDatas information, the AttackManager will choose the spawnpoints on which instances of the Attack Prefab will be spawned, but first we show warning icons on those spawnpoints to signal the player that an attack is coming from that direction. After a set time the warning icons are disabled and the Attack Prefabs are spawned, with given time offsets between each instance.

When an Attack Prefab is spawned, its own scripts will handle its behaviour from there. If it is a projectile, it will have a script that moves it on a given path, or if it uses gravity, a script will give it a start velocity and the built in physics engine will handle its movement from there. The Attack Prefabs also have their own colliders and when they collide with the player, they set the property "alive" on the players script to "false" signalling the game that the player has been hit and that the game should end.

After all necessary Attack Prefabs have been spawned, the AttackManager will wait for a given time before getting the next random weighted Attack Data and continuing its loop.

When the boss despawns, it will stop the connected Coroutines on the AttackManager, in turn ending the attack loop.

With this system, we can make many different attacks by just creating multiple AttackData objects, adjusting their values and assigning different Attack Prefabs to them. The whole system also works for different resolutions and screen sizes, as the spawnpoints for the attacks are part of a canvas which scales with the main camera.

After checking my options and going through some tutorials and reviews, I've decided to try out the tools "Pixel FX Designer" and "Pixel Composer". I started out with the first one, as it is more focused on what I needed for this project (pixel art, particle effects) and if I notice would that it doesn't fit my needs or I want to do something else for a specific projectile, I would switch over to the "Pixel Composer" which is more in-depth.

I hoped that with this approach I would be able to reduce the time it takes to create the attacks and learn some new skills while keeping the extra learning time and complexity low and keeping a somewhat coherent art style.

After figuring out how "Pixel FX Designer" works, I created one sprite for an attack and played around with dithering and resolution, to see which style I want to go for, so that I can apply the same options to the subsequent sprites of all the other attacks.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

When I was happy with the sprites of an attack, I'd export it out from "Pixel FX Designer", quickly touch it up in Aseprite and then import it into Unity, where I made Attack Prefabs with them.

In the end I made around 7 custom Effects in "Pixel FX Designer", 6 of which have been made into full Attack Prefabs. As I was quite happy with how the sprites turned out with "Pixel FX Designer", I never actually had to switch over to "Pixel Composer", which means that I was able to save quite some time, but never got to find out what is possible in that tool and how my workflow would have changed when using it.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Next time making projectiles I want to go back to the unity particle system and delve deeper into its secrets. "Pixel FX Designer" is nice because it is very simple, but one big drawback is that everything will be baked in in the end. That means you cannot augment the particles during gameplay, be it through gravity, through interaction with other objects or anything else. Making the particles directly in Unity will make all of those things possible.

After creating all the Attack Prefabs, I made fitting AttackData objects out of them and created 3-4 attacks for each boss. I also added some sound effects to all the Attack Prefabs that would play when they spawn or when they would hit the player.

When I was done with all the attacks, I was able to move on to the bosses themselves. As I already created most of the scripts and placeholder objects for them, all I needed was the sprites. Initially I wanted to give each boss an idle animation and maybe even attack animations, but to save time I chose to just create a static sprite for each of them. I started with "Moses" and "Michael" because both are human shaped, meaning I can use the same base template as I did for the player character.

As both characters are directly from the Bible, I used some old church illustrations from them as inspiration for my pixel art version. In hindsight, I could have given them more dynamic poses to still show some hints of movement, but for now I think they work well enough to give a visual representation to who is currently attacking you.

Progress report:

This week was used to add many things that aren't directly part of the game loop but are still necessary for a complete game.

A big part of this week's progress was finishing the bosses, by first creating the sprite for the boss "Behemoth" and after that adding music for all bosses.

I came up with the design for the Behemoth myself. The boss was initially meant to be Cerberus, that's why the design is doglike and has three heads, but as Cerberus is from Greek mythology and not mentioned in any Christian texts, I chose to just go with a different dog-/animal-like character from Christianity. I was also thinking of just calling the boss a "Hellhound", but I felt that "Behemoth" would fit better.

Now that I had all the bosses done, I wanted to add some music to them, which took longer than expected because I had issues finding fitting music for all the bosses. The first issue was to find three pieces of music that would fit to the bosses but also thematically fit to each other so that we don't have an extreme tonal shift from one bosses' music to the next. They would also have to be compatible with the sound effects that are already implemented, and best case the music should also loop. As a personal extra challenge, I chose to abstain from using any AI generated music, just as I tried with the sound effects.

That last additional requirement was something that made the search quite tricky, as nowadays it is difficult to judge what is generated by AI and what was made by hand, especially on "Pixabay", the platform that I used up until now, because as far as I know flagging uploaded media as AI generated was done by the uploaders themselves, who would probably have no incentives to actually flag their own content.

After struggling to find something that fits my needs on "Pixabay", I checked out some different platforms. One idea was to use classical music from well-known composers like Mozart or Bach, or just music used in church which would fit the theme of Christianity, but as the design of the game was more like early retro games and the sound effects were more cartoony, I abandoned that idea and chose to fixate more on music that incorporated chiptune/8-bit elements. After a long search, I finally found some pieces of music that I was happy with on the Platform "Zapsplat", which I will probably use more going forward. It has a bigger library of media fitting for games and seems to be less bloated with AI generated media in comparison to "Pixabay", at least for now.

After I chose my music, I updated my sound manager to also manage the boss music, which mostly works the same as the "PlayAmbience" function described in week 6. The only difference is that it starts and stops depending on if a boss is active or not.

After completing the bosses, I added some extra elements to make the stages more interesting and have them stand apart from each other a bit more. I added small particle effects for each stage with the Unity particle system, that would make the game feel a bit more alive and enhance the environment of the stages. Another easy thing I knew to add for better ambience was lighting. Just having some light sources in a scene can make a game look much better, so I added a spotlight to the player and some extra lights to the bosses and to most of the attacks and warning icons, highlighting the things that are important during gameplay. Because I figured that the global illumination wouldn't be the same over all the stages, especially in the first stage "Hell", I added a small script that would change the intensity of the global light when moving between stages.

I also added backgrounds for all the stages, finally getting rid of the default blue background that started to look quite out of place with all the custom pixel art that was in the game by now. For the backgrounds, I just made some quick sprites in Aseprite with the dither tool, imported them into unity and wrote a small script that would fade between the images when moving between stages.

Boss "Behemoth" with light sources on each eye:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Another thing I finally was able to get rid of was the default look of the start platform. Until now it was just a white rectangle, but I quickly designed a sprite for it, keeping its style aligned with that of the platforms from the first stage.

Now that the game looks and feels quite finished, I moved on to create everything around the game, starting with the start- and pause menus.

The design of the start menu was possible to finish quite quickly by reusing some assets that have already been created for the gameplay. I just created some extra sprites for the buttons and after that, added scripts that would handle the whole start menu logic.

For the pause menu, I just copied over the most relevant parts of the start menu and created a PauseMenuManager script, that would listen wait on the correct user input and then activate the menu and pause the game by setting Time.timeScale to zero. For unpausing the game, the manager just does the opposite, while also applying any changes the player has made to the settings.

## Week 9 - Dialogues and Finishing Touches

Worked hours: 23.5h

Progress report TLDR:

- Added win- and death screen
- Added tutorial
- Added dialogues to bosses
- Added new fonts

Progress report:

Even though this was the last week of the project, I still added some big features to the game, trying to improve the experience with each newly added thing.

One of the things the game definitely still needed were the win- and death screens, because those would be vital parts of the game loop, as they inform the player that the game is finished (one way or the other), and might show the next steps that the player can take, for example restarting the game.

In the end, I implemented these screens by simply adding two new canvas elements with text on them and creating animations for them so that they would move into frame when the player has either touched the goal platform or when the player has died. I also added a small sound effect for reaching the goal, just to make the experience a bit more fulfilling.

I also added a small tutorial, which meant that I could finally use the "Servant" character that I made in week 5 as the one that explains the game to the player. I wanted to keep the tutorial very short and concise, so that the player could easily understand the information and not get directly bored because they need to read through extremely long texts of explanations and lore.

The tutorial only explains the following things:

- The goal
- That there might be enemies that will attack the player
- that the player cannot fight back and instead of fighting, just has to move further up
- Small parts of the lore for the game

I've also written the tutorial in a way how I feel the "Servant" character would talk, although he now feels more like a manager than a servant, but that also works for my intentions.

Because I had to create a dialog system for the tutorial anyways, and still had some extra time, I decided to also add some dialogue to all the bosses, to have them interact a bit more with the character and explain their reasoning why they get in the way of the player. The system I made for that would also support multiple different dialogues for bosses, which would definitely be something I'd add in the future, as that makes replays much more interesting.

As a small additional style choice, I got some pixel art fonts from the creator "stormgold" on the platform "itch.io" and applied them to all the text that I now have in my game.

And then, after a lot of playtesting and bugfixing, the game was done.

# Conclusion

This project was mainly meant to help me figure out workflows for making games and game assets and getting used to all the tools that I'd use in that process. Learnings from this project are meant to help with the decision-making in future projects and should help me on my path forward of becoming something akin to a gamedev.

The game did take much longer than expected and the scope was adjusted multiple times during the process. Initially, I had hoped to finish the game in a bit more than a month. After I realised that that would just not be possible, I moved my deadline to the end of two months. Now, after nearly three months it is finally done, and I have realised during these three months that making a deadline for this project was something destined to fail from the start, because there were just way too many things that couldn't be quantified in their duration before doing them. Most of the things I did for this project were done for the first time or done for the first time in this particular way, so I had no reference for them to figure out how long they might take. The best I could do was to keep track of my time and try to move on from a task when I noticed it eating up too much of my time.

But as this project was meant to be a learning experience for future projects, it could be argued that it didn't really matter how long it would take, as most of the time spent on this project would in turn save me time in future projects, as I get more comfortable in my workflows, figure out how things are done the quickest way for the best results, and as I build a repertoire of my own scripts and objects, which I can reuse in future projects.

In the end, I'm very glad that I didn't stop the process halfway through just because my initial arbitrary deadline was due and I'm quite happy with the result and what I've learned through this project. I might continue with this game at a later point in time, adding more stages, bosses and so on, but for now I would like to work on some other projects, to learn some more techniques and generally get better at making all kinds of games.

# Acknowledgements

I would like to thank my friends and family for supporting me in this endeavour and assisting in parts with brainstorming, playtesting, and decision-making. They also greatly helped with keeping me motivated, by regularly checking in, coming up with ideas on their own and generally just showing interest in my creations. Without their help, this project might have taken way longer or wouldn't have been finished at all.
